<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
  Central page content.

  Edit THIS single file to customize any page's content without touching the
  individual page files (*.aspx / *.aspx.cs).

  How it works
  ============
  Each page's LoadPageContent() sets the built-in default content. Anything you
  define here overrides that default. Web.config "Page.*" appSettings override
  this file. So the precedence is:

      Web.config  >  this file (PageContent.xml)  >  LoadPageContent() defaults

  Changes here take effect immediately (the file is watched); no rebuild needed.

  Structure
  =========
    <page key="Default" title="Optional browser title">
        <box id="cbWelcome" header="Optional header text"><![CDATA[
            Any HTML for this ContentBox goes here.
        ]]></box>
        <literal id="litSomething"><![CDATA[ text for a Literal control ]]></literal>
    </page>

    - key    = page class name (e.g. Default, About, FAQ, Donations, Privacy,
               Legal, ReadThisFirst).
    - box id / literal id = the control's ID as it appears in the .aspx markup.
    - Put HTML inside <![CDATA[ ... ]]> so you don't have to escape < > & or quotes.
    - "header" attribute is optional; omit it to keep the header from the markup.

  Available control IDs per page
  ==============================
    Default        : cbWelcome, cbAbout, cbFeatures, cbGetStarted
    About          : cbAbout, cbHowItWorks, cbHistory, cbContact, cbLegal
    FAQ            : cbGeneral, cbCompatibility, cbUpdates
    Donations      : cbSupport, cbHowToHelp
    Privacy        : cbInfoCollect, cbInfoUse, cbDataSecurity, cbContact
    Legal          : cbDisclaimer, cbLicense, cbTrademarks, cbLiability
    ReadThisFirst  : cbTOC, cbDisclaimer, cbWelcome, cbFeatures, cbStarted

  Example (remove the surrounding comment to activate):

    <page key="Default">
        <box id="cbWelcome" header="Welcome!"><![CDATA[
            <p>Your custom welcome text here.</p>
        ]]></box>
    </page>
-->
<content>

  <!-- Add <page> entries below to override content. Empty by default so the
       built-in LoadPageContent() defaults are used until you customize. -->

</content>
